But the reason this works? It's because the ability to 'query' itself, the ability to submit a prompt and receive a response, is in fact a concrete example of an absential in motion.

You specify a shape and GPT presses that shape against its Dao and returns what comes out.
We developed a compressed file format for large LD matrices and a tool to efficiently query the data by using the many nice features of HDF5 file format

No query that you submit to GPT can return that Dao. The Dao cannot be named, let alone serialized into JSON.

What it can do is return a slice of the Dao that we hope includes enough of the relations that we care about to be interesting.

An interesting case: HyDE may bias open-ended queries. Given the query ‚ÄúWhat would the author say about art vs. engineering?‚Äù, HyDE's answer 1) is more essay-specific than the non-HyDE answer, but 2) more biased.

Whether this is more acc is up to your interpretation! https://t.co/j9qsVruKcC

Where HyDE may not work well: HyDE may mislead when the query is ‚Äúmis-hallucinated‚Äù given lack of context.

For instance given the query ‚ÄúWhat is Bel?‚Äù, HyDE hallucinates a Semitic god, but in the article it is a programming language. https://t.co/nrNpx1UlYg

Where HyDE can work well: answering temporal queries. In our @paulg essay example, HyDE does better on answering ‚Äúwhat did PG do after going to RISD‚Äù vs. the raw query.

The answer w/o HyDE blends past+present on PG‚Äôs art experience. The answer with HyDE is much more accurateüñºÔ∏è https://t.co/rWEzjvocLW

Refresher on HyDE: generate hypothetical answer(s), and embed that hypothetical answer instead of the original query to perform lookup/retrieval.

A very interesting technique where the hallucinated answer is better suited for retrieval than the original query.

The centerpoint theorem gives the existence of deep query points for Tukey depth, thus Rousseeuw and Hubert, who introduced regression depth, conjectured the analogous result for regression depth. This was shown to be true in 2000 by Amenta, Bern, Eppstein and Teng.
